It is running and stops mid cut.

I suspect that these VFD are undersized for the spindle. The specs claim that it is a 2.2 kW spindle but if you put even half a kilowatt of load on one the VFD just gives up and throws this error.

I’m not 100% sure what VFD the Omio uses, but I did some Googling and someone said it uses the NOWFOREVER E-100. According to the manual, E004 means an undervoltage error. Does this problem seem to happen with heavy cuts?

MidnightSlate:

According to the manual, E004 means an undervoltage error

I took a look at the manual and I think we have a winner!

image708×93 17.5 KB

After skimming through the manual I get the feeling that these are really meant to be used at 220V and when used at 110 it doesn’t leave much margin for voltage drop. The error refers to voltage on the DC bus, and it looks like it is possible to read the voltage while it is running:

image714×884 117 KB

image700×225 22.9 KB

MidnightSlate:

Does this problem seem to happen with heavy cuts?

Absolutely. When I face the spoil board on my router using a 2inch+ cutter I have to cut a very shallow depth and if I exceed a certain amount it will trigger this error consistently.

It happens during long contour cuts in AL. It might be the bit gumming up. I am not real aggressive on my cuts. 40in/min 24000 RPM .065" depth of cut. 4mm single flute from a reputable FRC supplier. In this instance the bit may have pulled out of the collet to increase the DOC. I broke my last 4mm so have to finish the cut using a 6 MM bit with no issues.

As the VFD goes. I am running a 220V VFD. I do need to check my incoming voltage. It might of a lighting transformer and only 208V. Why does the world has to have so many "standard voltages, I will never know. I thought 120 was low for the power requirements when I bought it. VFD take the incoming power, rectify it to make a DC bus voltage. Chop that up to get the variable frequency/voltage to feed the 3 phase output.

That’s unusual. Your cutting parameters are very reasonable and I expect the required spindle power to be well under 750W. I have never ran a 220V VFD on 208, but it seems odd that the input voltage being 6% lower would cause issues. Your setup seems good, hopefully, it’s something simple like a parameter setting or a minor electrical issue rather than a dead VFD.
